## Triage

M1a adds portable reference identity (ContributionRef, LiveSourceRef, MaterialRef, contributionRefKey) and a host-owned additive contribution index to ExtensionRuntime before graph projection becomes authority. It also reserves graph-owned patch vocabulary and extracts shader-scope validation into host composition validation. The existing FamilyContributionRef, RenderMaterialRef, timeline-domain shader validation, and TIMELINE_PATCH_RESERVED_OP_FAMILIES provide partial foundations, but six integration boundaries are unresolved: (1) the exact shape and barrel placement of new reference contracts vs existing FamilyContributionRef; (2) the contribution-index entry shape that must span active, inactive, reserved, disabled, and invalid entries with duplicate resolutionPolicy; (3) which graph-owned op families and diff granularities to reserve beyond the existing clip.split/clip.slice; (4) where shader-scope validation should land in the host composition layer and what the narrow projection helper looks like; (5) how route-fit metadata flows from RenderPlannerResult into the index; (6) the schema contract surface for any new vocabulary shapes.

## Research Areas

1. reference-contract-gap: Map the gap between existing FamilyContributionRef<TContribution> (contribution + extensionId pair) and the needed ContributionRef (scoped by extensionId, kind, contributionId). Determine whether ContributionRef extends, wraps, or replaces FamilyContributionRef for the index key path. Identify the exact shape of LiveSourceRef given the existing LiveSource interface, and confirm MaterialRef as a type alias of RenderMaterialRef. Locate the barrel insertion point in src/sdk/index.ts and the canonical module path under src/sdk/.
2. contribution-index-design: Design the contribution-index entry shape that must cover active descriptors, inactive/reserved metadata, disabled/invalid entries, package state, route metadata where known, and diagnostics — all host-owned and data-only. Determine how assembleExtensionRuntime populates the index alongside existing inactiveReserved, knownRenderIds, and packageStateInventory. Resolve how duplicate scoped-key declarations produce multiple index entries with structured resolutionPolicy and how that interacts with the existing cross-extension duplicate-contribution diagnostic in FamilyContributionSequence.
3. graph-patch-vocabulary: Audit the current TIMELINE_PATCH_RESERVED_OP_FAMILIES (clip.split, clip.slice) and TIMELINE_DIFF_GRANULARITIES (clip, track, asset, app, project-data). Identify which graph-owned families (e.g., graph.node.*, graph.edge.*, graph.group.*) and granularities (e.g., graph, node, edge) need to be reserved as known-but-non-executable, following the existing pattern. Determine the addition point in src/sdk/video/timeline/patch.ts and any downstream consumers in timeline-patch.ts validation that need to recognize the new reserved families.
4. shader-scope-extraction: Trace the current shader_scope_occupied validation across timeline-domain.ts (assignTimelineClipShader, assignTimelinePostprocessShader, validateTimelineConfigSnapshot), timeline-patch.ts (patch validation), and renderPlanner.ts (shader composition dedup). Plan extraction into a host-composition validation module while keeping existing shader scope tests green. Define the narrow shader projection helper that maps existing snapshot shader refs (TimelineShaderSummary) through the new contribution index for existing callers.
5. route-fit-normalization: Map how route metadata (RenderRoutePlan.route, determinism, blockers) flows from the existing planRender output (RenderPlannerResult) into the new contribution index entries. The task specifies normalizing route fit using existing planner outputs only — determine what subset of RenderPlannerResult fields surfaces as route metadata in the index and how route-fit is represented as a normalized shape. Ensure RenderPlannerResult shape remains backward compatible.
